Change and growth are essential to creating the life you want. 

Without it life and dreams become stagnant and you can easily slip into a phase of ongoing waiting, anxiety,  or even depression. 

The ability to become sufficient means continual growth, continual learning, continual modification, continual improvement of a plan that was established when you first began. 

For almost 9 years this has been our life. Starting with backyard chickens and a garden which failed miserably.  Together we learned -

How to preserve foods.

 How to raise meat and process it.

How to grow a garden and the importance of foraging.

How to incorporate livestock that will serve a greater purpose.. 

The one animal that Justin has always dreamed of owning...donkeys. Well, his dreams has come true. Did I want donkeys? No. But he has a vision for the purpose of them, so I'll follow his lead. 

All that to say, the young donkeys are coming home! 

Together, he and our oldest have been working on the new donkey barn and the addition to the goat barn. I'm excited to see it completed!

Change and growth. This is what our journey is about. If you can't flex with this life you're going to need to learn how to. Also, if you don't enjoy the journey your currently on then discover why and change the path.

It doesn't mean quit, it simply means pull back until you're ready for the next phase. Just remember, the next phase must happen to grow.

Let's talk goats, shall we? 

Let me convince those considering goats to wait. I have now fallen out of favor with many of you...

1. Know your purpose behind getting them. Meat, milk, clear the land? Once you determine that RESEARCH breeds. If it's to clear land then you should get wethers.

2. Whatcha going to do with all the kids once you start breeding? Sell them, keep them all, or put some into the freezer? Goats can pile up fast so you're going to need a plan of action once you start breeding. 

3. Registered or not registered? This will depend on why you're raising them. Keep in mind, if you are intending to sell them many people prefer goats to be registered.

4. Take your time and build adequate housing, stalls and solid fencing. They are escape artists and this WILL frustrate you to no end. 

5. Do not raise goats with the intentions of making just goat milk soap. Discover what else can be achieved with the milk. I love goat milk and prefer drinking it over cow milk. 

6. If you're going to keep your goats on pasture you MUST plan to move them regularly. Goats were not designed by God to be kept in a pasture grazing like sheep or cows. They were created to forage brush; thick unwanted, invasive brush. Items that other rumnant animals will not consume. When a goat herd overgrazes a space the risk of contracting parasites increases. 

7. Minerals, salt rock, baking soda, and fresh water is a must. Know if your land is selenium deficient. There is nothing worse than your goat or herd coming down with White Muscle Disease. We use @redmondagriculture minerals which contain selenium and they love it. 

8. Know that a wether is more susceptible to contracting uninary calculie. Do not offer a rich diet, provide water with a little raw AVC, in it, and have a salt rock (keeps them drinking) available at all times.

9. A buck is a pain in the ass if you cannot keep him contained. He will do WHATEVER it takes to get to he does in heat. This will make you misslerable. 

10. No you cannot cuddle little goats all day as you have a homestead to run. 

Now, go forth and properly plan to incorporate your herd!

I was once that woman.  The one that kept scented plug-ins in every outlet and battery operated scented sprayers in every room…yes, in the beginning of our homesteading journey I used the chemical stuff, but I swear it didn’t last long. 

I remember a time when my husband would secretly gather up the plug-ins & sprayers, immediately rehoming them to the trash can.  I’d then replace each and every one, swearing that they made the house smell nice.

The battle between us continued until the children began complaining of headaches, and that’s when I knew that my chemical scented plug-ins needed to go.  In my defense, I used them because I was constantly trying to mask the smells found in a homesteading house ~2 dogs, a cat, sometimes a sick chicken in the bathroom, or a poultry brooder in the living room~ there were a LOT of stinky smells in our little farmhouse!

The stinky farmhouse oders didn’t last once I discovered essential oils, and soon good scents began to float through the air.  Not only did the house smelling nice, our moods were lifted based on the essential oil blends we chose to incorporate in the cold air diffusers. 

However, I consider myself to be a pretty practical person and the thought of placing a cold air diffuser in the bathrooms didn’t make much sense to me.  What did make sense was placing reed diffusers into small spaces around the house, they worked to purify the air or simply provide a clean smell.

The opportunity to grow, raise, and sell food should never be illegal or something we have to fight for. The overreach of our goverment to control the food source makes them the, for a lack of words (maybe not), enemy to the people. 

The biggest fight among many farmers? Raw milk and the opportunity to sell it freely. I can see why this is a focus for so many, BUT what about:

Food Clubs
PMAs
Farm Shares 
Private sales of food without goverment overreach 

The testimony of how so many farms have been raided, threatened, and fined by offering services as this is unexceptable. When does it stop?

The answer is simple, when your community stands up together and says, no more, enough is enough. We will not be controlled, and we will do what a free country does, live freely. 

If you ever have the opportunity to attend the Rogue Food Conference do so. I walked away feeling validated that what we want for @acorn.creek.farmstead needs to happen.

Does this mean we'll be breaking the law? It depends on what you accept as being legal or illegal. Feeding people should never be illegal, and neither should making a business out of it. 

For 2023 I am going to encourage you to say, enough is enough. Stop goverment overreach to discontinue being enslaved. 

If you're fearful of being slapped with a cease and desist order, fined or threatened to be arrested then its time to reevaluate your desire to homestead or farmstead. Feeding yourself and others is not free, but it's time to make it happen.

Go Rogue.

In a nutshell, this is me. Everything you need to know about me is in this short clip.

I'm Ann. I'm half Thai and half Italian, daughter of the most high,  military brat,  a woman who deals with depression and anxiety daily (controlled by food, body movement, vitamin D, CBD - this is how I handle it), lover of all things old, seeker of minimizing our footprints left behind, firm believer that good health comes from good gut health, and straight shooter who's learning grace.

I did not come from a homesteading or farming background; 9 years has been spent on educating ourselves. In this journey I've failed, succeeded, cried, became frustrated, BUT I got up the next day and started again. 

This life has been a journey of personal growth, which has allowed me to do what I do and share it with others. 

I farm.
Today marks 1 year in Tennessee and I can't tell you how much being here has changed our lives. We went from 2 acres to 42. We've remained focus on the direction which we've been called to head.

I offer farm shares.
For those who can't farm but seek to eat a clean healthy food choice, we have you covered.

I teach hands-on workshops on our farm. Teaching people how to live a more sustainable life through food preservation, poultry & rabbit processing, fermenting, kombucha making, infastructure tours. We have also contracted instructors who teach farmhouse sourdough,  herbalism,  and hog processing.

I am an author.
The Farm Girl's Guide to Preserving the Harvest has lead so many to create a more sustainable life through food preservation. Food freedom allows you to offer your family healthier food choices.

I speak at conferences. 
There's something about encouraging others to move forward in living a traditional life.

I live by example. 
What you see is what you get. If I fail, you'll know. If I succeeded, you'll know. If I don't know what the heck I'm doing, you'll know because I'll ask for help.

I hide nothing. 
I don't lie. Jokes fly above my head. I speak a dual language in my head (Thai & Englush). I've been know to cry like a baby as I and others  celebrate successes. I'm direct which stem from my inability to lie.
 
Ready to join the journey?

Duck foot injury. This is bound to happen when raising ducks. More times than not, it is going to happen more than once. Learn how to treat injuries naturally with a few basic items.

Owning ducks should come with a label which reads, “A duck foot injury is bound to happen. Regardless.” How could it not when webbed feet are concerned?

Ducks are prone to easily receive cuts on their feet, but a more serious issue is when bumblefoot sets in.  Thankfully, both can be treated naturally without the use of over the counter medicines.  And this should be the ultimate goal.

We’ve had our fair share of injuries and illness in the property.  However, a duck foot injury is one which seems to always have me worrying more than any other issue.  The weight of a duck’s body puts quite a bit of pressure onto their legs and feet, making recover slow.  Longer than what it would take other poultry (chicken, turkey, even guinea) to recover, resulting in at times weeks longer.

Much like how we treat ourselves, our small livestock is also treated through the a strong holistic practice.  The use of natural items is effective. The use of colloidal silver, essential oils, and herbs is used daily on our homestead. Keep in mind, natural items are used for both humans and livestock.

A duck foot injury, such as a cut, can easily be treated holistically.  Though it does takes being proactive when treating it, and, at times, it may require regular monitoring for awhile.

Raising Coturnix Quail is a great way to incorporate a protein onto the property. Domesticated quail offer a tasty meat option and are prolific egg layers. Not to mention, quail are an ideal option for those with a smaller property, and are extremely easy to raise.

Quail come in a variety of species, though the most commonly raised are the Coturnix quail. Consider the term Coturnix to be the general variety. Under this generic head category fall a variety of species; Texas A&M, Cinnamon, Manchurian Golden, Tuxedo, British Range, English White, and Pharoah D1.

In order to create a larger species for meat and egg production many will cross breed species. For example, breeding Texas A&M to Pharoah D1 will provide a larger species which is also a prolific egg layer, laying an average of 300 eggs per year.

Unlike may poultry, domestic quail, like the Coturnix, can not independently free range. Meaning, they will not return the coop each day. Because quail spook easily, keeping them in a movable poultry tractor may result in injury as they try to take flight.

Do not devalue small family farms. We already fight our government for our rights to provide food for our community, so the last thing we want to do is prove to the consumer market that we are priced appropriately. 

Please don't sell me on organic verses nonGMO grains, I've heavily done my research and know the family farm which I purchase my nonGMO feed from. That same farm grows, harvests, and bags their goods. I know if they spray or don't spray. I know why they choose to not file for an organic tag. 

You see, so many consumers love the organic tag and immediately buy into it without further research. However, the small family farms that will not buy into the outrageous labeling cost to file certified organic have no other option but to liable their feeds as nonGMO. 

Sad, isn't it?

Then, we move to the corn/soy ingredients. But, that's a fight for a different day, and one I'll revisit later.

I'm going to leave my other producers this for now, do not undersell the local farms in your area. Here's marketing 1 on 1:

1. You undervalue your product. Yep, you do. A product priced higher is seen as having more value, and maybe It does. 

2. You can create a bad relationship with other farmers in your area. 

3. If you choose to discontinue selling your goods, you've left the consumer with sticker shock when they purchase elsewhere. And we, as the new producer, have to educate them on the value and cost it actually takes to provide the product they wish to consume. Which MAY cause them to stray from purchasing clean foods raised or grown by a local farmer. 

Again, our fight as small family farms is with our government , which means we producers should work together and price together. 

And don't worry, there's not enough of us to oversatirate the market, and I promise you, God will not favore you more because you're selling your wares for less than its value. 

If you've ever attended one of my talks on Creating a Profitable Honestead, this is additional information that would have gone into this talk. 

PS. @janellelynnanderson and I are supporting my sweet friend Theron and his new business @mothernbrothers !

Keep a healthy flock of backyard chickens by learning how to beat coccidiosis. Coccidiosis in chickens, other poultry, and livestock is extremely deadly. By establishing a strong natural preventative plan, solid bio-security measures, and knowing what to offer as a coccidiosis treatment can save the lives of your flock.

Coccidiosis is a single cell microscopic parasite. It enters the chicken’s body when a bird ingests the Coccidia egg. This egg is usually found on the ground or the floor of the coop.

The Coccidia parasite begins to colonize and multiply within the gut wall. Over time the parasite is shed through the feces of the chicken, and the vicious cycle will continue until the bird is treated or dead.

At this point, a new host (or hosts) can become infected when it accidentally consumes waste which contains the Coccidia parasite. This is the point in which the disease spreads like wildfire.

Canning pumpkin is necessary to preserve the pumpkin harvest. Included are tips for preserving winter squash of all varieties, and delicious pumpkin puree recipes. Everything pumpkin, yes? Definitely, yes!

Preserving sugar pumpkin is a must, as it does not have a long shelf life in its fresh form. Unlike sugar pumpkins, winter squash and large pumpkins can successfully be stored long term in their raw form.

Winter squash stores well for many months in a root cellar or cold storage space. How long will depend on the variety being stored.

Winter Squash Stored Fresh

Pumpkin, Sugar – 1 to 3 months
Pumpkin, Large – 3 to 4 months
Acorn – 1 to 3 months
Spaghetti – 1 to 3 months (not able to be canned due to being unable to cubed for canning)
Butternut – up to 6 months
Blue Hubbard – 6 to 7 months

Because pumpkin and winter squashes are low in acidity, a pressure canner is the only tool available to make this fall staple shelf stable. Yeah, say that 3 times!

I will not pretend I sell pet milk in place of real, unpasteurized milk. Nor will I label my jars as pet milk, which is what the state of Tennessee requires from those of us who sell real milk.

I will not be told I can not sell milk, yogurt, butter, cream, and buttermilk. When has real food items become illegal to offer?

I will not pretend my government dictates this to protect the health of others because they care.

I will not sell USDA cuts off our farm. Why would I allow our government free access to my property?

I not only sell whole pasture raised chicken, but I also sell parted birds. Someone, please explain to me why this is illegal. 

Some of you follow the laws established, and that's okay. You have to do you. 

For us and our farm, we will continue to push food freedom as a producer who sells our goods locally to those who seek to consume a clean food source from a trusted family farm. 

Amen.

"I am scared to death about buying food from the grocery store, especially meat." - my husband, Justin.

Every evening, we milk together and recap the day, talk, and pray together. Last night's conversation was a strong one, and one I hope that people are willing to talk about. 

Preach about. 

Share.

And know how important and essential our life is. 

Basically,  here's what was said -

This life isn't about instant gratification. It's about daily hard work, even on the days you just want to sit and sip your coffee, sleep in, keep warm.

It's about waiting. Planning is key to a successful homestead/farm.

Anticipate and wait is what we do. Nothing in this life is instant.

We better our infrastructure as we wait. We breed, grow, and preserve food because we know it will sustain us but also keep us healthy.

If we are not willing to learn, execute, and accept this, then we fail. 

In short, we put our entire lives, every hour, minute, second, to know that we will not have to purchase meat or pestocide tainted vegetables from the market. That we control our dairy products, fresh eggs, and even honey or maple syrup. 

We are the few that the government fears. They can't control our food source, which means they can not control us.

He did write the forward for my book.

He and I should never sit next to each other during conference Q&A time because we're not very well-behaved.

He takes the time to come say hello if he sees me first. 

And he ALWAYS asks for an update since the last time we saw each other.

Joel is an advocate for those who live the life I live, but also a nice guy.

More importantly, he went to bat for me when I least expected it. 

The dude's alright.

Hi, my name is Ann, and I break all the rules. Even the ones my husband sets for me. 

Yep, that's Rosemary. In the carport, free-standing while being milked. Also, this is THE most incredible milk machine ever.

That's all.

My 8 year old self knew I wanted to own a farm.

My teen self wanted to hang out in the beaches of Hawai'i basking in the sun

My twenty year old self wanted to make money to travel. 

My thirty year old self desperately tried to raise 7 kids in the suburbs.

My forty year old self achieved her dreams. 

Justin and I have worked extremely hard to allow the farm to provide for us. After 1  year and 10 months, it does exactly this.

Not only does the farm feed us, but it also feeds our community. Though it doesn't stop at this. We have also been called to teach. Acorn Creek Farmstead also hosts hands-on workshops to teach others how to achieve this life. 

My 50 year old self...well, she is still in awe of where God has taken her.

Is the carport an ideal spot to milk your cows? 

Even if you have a space in the barn to milk them?

The answer is yes, a million times over. Absolutely, yes. 

If you haven't guessed by now, this isn't the most dreamy or picturesque location to milk my cows, but it does have electricity, access to hot water, and it is much easier for me to clean the milk machine here than in the barn. 

By the girls' next lactation, we'll have the milk barn ready to go and let me tell you. I'll be ready for it too. 

If I haven't normalized owning a family milk cow to those who drive by the farm, then well, I don't know what does.

An unpopular opinion on homesteading.  Or is it?

Welcome to homestead living friend. Where growing and raising food, preserving it, and constant cleaning and washing is how we choose to live our lives. 

Isn't it grand? It absolutely is! Amen.
Life is measured by moments. And Amen.

Freedom is a very powerful thing. The freer you are, the more people fear you. 

Not only does the government fear you, but also the common man. 

When you choose health freedom, financial freedom, and food freedom, you become the different one. The odd one. The one that does not comply, and you are the one that stinds firm for the sake of all mankind. We will not be dictated to and hope people realize how important it is to think freely. 

You become dangerous to those in power.

How can a group of individuals who seek to better the land, create less waste, live more intentionally, and seek to be reliant on ourselves be dangerous?

Because we question corruption and control, as well as question those who state they care and seek to better the world under the guise of evil.

This world does not belong to those who seek to control it. However, it is freely given to them when your voice and actions do not commant attention.

Stand fast, my friends. Now is the time to speak truths and live by example. Freedom is not free. You simply have to make the decision that it IS worth fighting for.

Goose is, in fact, a goose! Here's her story...

Now the question is, do we want to add a gander? We've raised geese for many years, and I can't seem to convince myself that we need to add a gander to the farm. I'm seriously toying with just adding another goose.

The incredible goose was raised as a gosling with the chicks, and together, they moved to the coop. She has been very protective of her flock, and if the rooster gets a little carried away, she will put them in their place.

She is also the last one in the coop, but never before, she circles the house one time. From patrolling the house, she goes and stands in her pool until she is escorted to the coop for the night. 

She has become exactly what we had hoped for, a guard goose with is calm (so far) and protective of her flock. 

I guess we'll wait until spring to see what we'll end up deciding...add a gander or another goose.

Death pulls on our emotions. Sometimes so fierce that as you're reminiscing, you will either be a sobbing hot mess one minute and laughing hysterically the next. 

We cared for Justin's momma from October 2022 through April 2023. It was filled with some very thoughtful times. I was responsible for sorting through her items, and luckily, it was an easy task. 

Before she became to ill to speak or care for herself, she asked me to minimize and get red of all the unnecessary things she collected. So I did. 

I kept pieces for her grandchildren and a few pieces for Justin and his brother, but everything else went. 

This copper piece, it stayed with me. It's a wall vace for dried flowers, a hammer and nail created the design, and assembled with additional copper pieces. 

I had fallen in love with it over 19 years ago, and it is now getting a home in my kitchen.

She was an orner and sometimes grumpy woman, but man, did she ever love her sons and grandchildren. 

Nancy, you're so missed, and I am excited for the day we will connect once again at the feet of our Father.

I have lost myself to reclaim myself.

We are 1 month shy of being on the farm for 2 years. In these two years, I had to put my home on the back burner to get our farm up and running. 

Justin and I focused on not inky feeding ourselves, but also our community.  We launched workshops to teach a more traditional and sustainable way of living. 

But now, the seasons have shifted. The farm is functioning and thriving, but there's always work to be done to keep it going, and we are in a good place for continual growth.

Now is the time to work on my space. The place that fills me with comfort and ease. The house was built in the early 70s and, over the years, has remained in its original form. 

It's time to breathe new, well old life back into it. This photo represents a few things - 

It is one of my most favorite spots in our small kitchen. The antique side buffet is old, worn, and not in great shape, but it has a story to tell. 

The shelves above it come from the boardwalk that Justin and I had our first date. 

The books that sit in the selves hold books from author friends of mine and vintage cookbooks that contain recipes using veal, duck, lamb, and real food ingredients. 

The kitchen and floor will receive a remodeling next winter, but the walls will be painted soon to freshen up the space. 

This year, our focus is on removing the brown shag carpet, laying new flooring, and painting the walls throughout the house. 

It's time to make this Hine ours, and I hope you're ready for the journey!
